---
// Programmer's Curation Checklist — grounded in established festival
// programming practice. Draws on the BFI's "Programming for Audiences"
// toolkit, the Sundance Institute's selection-criteria language, IFFR / IDFA
// "ethics of representation" conversations on documentary subjects, and
// Toronto / Berlinale curatorial practice on lineup balance.
---
<div class="panel p-6 md:p-10 print:bg-white print:text-black">
  <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-gold-400">Programmer's Curation Checklist</p>
  <h3 class="mt-1 font-display text-2xl text-white">
    10 questions to ask of a curated lineup.
  </h3>
  <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-white/60 max-w-2xl">
    Built on practice that festival programmers, syllabus designers, and
    public-broadcaster programmers already use:
    <span class="text-white">the BFI Programming for Audiences toolkit</span>,
    <span class="text-white">Sundance Institute's selection rubric</span>
    (vision · craft · originality · impact),
    <span class="text-white">IFFR's and IDFA's ethics-of-representation
    conventions</span> for documentary subjects, and the
    <span class="text-white">"5 axes of programming"</span> approach used at
    Toronto and Berlinale (gender, geography, generation, genre, gravity).
    Each question below maps to one of those frameworks and translates it
    into a decision a programmer can put on a final-selection meeting agenda.
  </p>

  <ol class="mt-8 grid gap-3 md:grid-cols-2 text-sm leading-relaxed">
    <!-- Pillar 1 — Programming argument (curator's statement) -->
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">1 · Programming argument</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">01.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">State the program's argument in one sentence. <span class="text-white/55">(BFI: "the curatorial intent in 30 words." Sundance: the program statement.)</span></span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">1 · Programming argument</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">02.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">If a viewer left after seeing only the first three films, what would they conclude is "normal" — and is that the conclusion you wanted them to reach?</span>
    </li>

    <!-- Pillar 2 — Authorship & voice (Sundance, Berlinale, Toronto curatorial criteria) -->
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">2 · Authorship & voice</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">03.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">What share of the films are directed, written, or produced by women? <span class="text-white/55">(Berlinale's gender pledge: 50/50 by 2020. Sundance: tracked since 2002.)</span></span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">2 · Authorship & voice</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">04.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">For films depicting subjects from a specific community, are members of that community involved as authors of the work — not only as subjects? <span class="text-white/55">(IFFR / IDFA ethics-of-representation standard.)</span></span>
    </li>

    <!-- Pillar 3 — Treatment & representation (IFFR, IDFA, Hot Docs ethics conversations) -->
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">3 · Treatment & representation</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">05.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">For films staging shame around victimhood (harassment, violence, abuse), how does the scene resolve — restitution, consequence, or silence? Does the program's framing equip the audience to read the resolution?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">3 · Treatment & representation</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">06.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">Have you included at least one film that breaks the modal treatment of the program's central theme — a counter-pattern that gives the audience a third option?</span>
    </li>

    <!-- Pillar 4 — Lineup balance (Toronto / Berlinale "5 axes": gender, geography, generation, genre, gravity) -->
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">4 · Lineup balance</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">07.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">On each of the five programming axes — <em>gender, geography, generation, genre, gravity</em> — which is over-represented, and which is missing? Which gap is intentional?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">4 · Lineup balance</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">08.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">Where does the lineup show <em>convergence</em> across cultures (themes both sides treat similarly), and where does it show <em>divergence</em>? Is your program's argument legible without explanation?</span>
    </li>

    <!-- Pillar 5 — Audience access & accountability (BFI Programming for Audiences) -->
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">5 · Audience & accountability</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">09.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">Who is the target audience for this program, and what is the path from announcement to seats? <span class="text-white/55">(BFI's "reach × frequency × depth" frame.)</span></span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gold-400/70 mb-1">5 · Audience & accountability</p>
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">10.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">After the program runs, what one metric will tell you whether it landed — attendance, audience composition, post-screening discussion quality, critical reception, follow-on programming demand — and how will you collect it?</span>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p class="mt-6 text-xs text-white/45 max-w-3xl leading-relaxed">
    <span class="text-white/60">Sources:</span>
    BFI "Programming for Audiences" toolkit
    (<a href="https://www.bfi.org.uk/supporting-uk-film/film-fund/exhibition-funding" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-gold-400/80 hover:underline">bfi.org.uk</a>);
    Sundance Institute selection criteria
    (<a href="https://www.sundance.org/festivals/sundance-film-festival" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-gold-400/80 hover:underline">sundance.org</a>);
    IFFR / IDFA ethics-of-representation conventions for documentary subjects;
    Berlinale 50/50 by 2020 pledge; Toronto / IFFR curatorial practice on
    lineup balance ("five axes" framework).
  </p>

  <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 text-xs text-white/40">
    <button onclick="window.print()" class="rounded-full bg-white/5 px-4 py-2 text-white/70 ring-1 ring-white/10 hover:bg-white/10 hover:text-white transition print:hidden">
      Print this checklist
    </button>
    <span>or screenshot — it's CC-BY.</span>
  </div>
</div>
